body:
I have written custom assertion classes and methods following the approach described in the [official documentation](http://joel-costigliola.github.io/assertj/assertj-core-custom-assertions.html).

However, when I use my custom assertion classes softly (using a custom soft assertions class that extends `SoftAssertions`), my custom assertion methods will throw `NullPointerException`s instead of failing cleanly when the object being asserted on is unexpectedly `null`.

I've documented a very simple example of what I'm doing below, as well as a couple of workarounds, neither of which I am comfortable with.
##### Example

To demonstrate this problem with familiar code, I created a project using the `TolkienCharacter` and `TolkienCharacterAssert` classes documented [here](http://joel-costigliola.github.io/assertj/assertj-core-custom-assertions.html)

To make these classes operational, I added the necessary getters to the `TolkienCharacter` class and created an empty `Race` class.

Then I created a simple class to enable soft assertions on the `TolkienCharacterAssert` class.  It looks like this:

``` java
import org.assertj.core.api.SoftAssertions;

public class TolkienSoftAssertions extends SoftAssertions {

        public TolkienCharacterAssert assertThat(TolkienCharacter actual) {
                return proxy(TolkienCharacterAssert.class, TolkienCharacter.class, actual);
        }
}
```

Then I created a simple class to test my `SoftAssertions`:

``` java
public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        TolkienCharacter frodo = new TolkienCharacter();
        TolkienCharacter samnullGamgee = null;
        TolkienSoftAssertions softly = new TolkienSoftAssertions();
        softly.assertThat(frodo).hasAge(10); // Expect failure - age will be 0 due to not being initialized.
        softly.assertThat(samnullGamgee).hasAge(11); // Expect failure - argument is null.
        softly.assertAll();
    }
}
```

When I run this class, I get a `NullPointerException` when asserting on `samnullGamgee`.  It occurs in the `if`-statement in the `hasAge` method, which I've included below for convenience:

``` java
public TolkienCharacterAssert hasAge(int age) {
    // check that actual TolkienCharacter we want to make assertions on is not null.
    isNotNull();

    // check condition
    if (actual.getAge() != age) {
        failWithMessage("Expected character's age to be <%s> but was <%s>", age, actual.getAge());
    }

    // return the current assertion for method chaining
    return this;
}
```
##### Workaround

I found two ways to work around this problem.

A. Update the line containing the `if`-statement to

```
    if (actual != null & actual.getAge() != age)
```

I'm not a huge fan of this approach.  It seems to defeat the purpose of the call to `isNotNull()`, and it makes the code a bit less readable.

B. Replace the line containing `isNotNull()` with

```
    Objects.instance().assertNotNull(info, actual)
```

Unfortunately, the `Objects` class is in the package `org.assertj.core.internal`, which makes me leery of using it.
